07 until his resignation in 2009 to run for the 2010 Republican nomination for [[Governor of Alabama]].<ref>[http://www.accs.cc/PDFs/News%20Release%20-%20Byrne%20Resigns-Board%20Appoints%20Interim%20Chancellor%20-%20052809.pdf ACCS Press Release: State Board of Education appoints Joan Davis as interim chancellor]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://byrneforalabama.com |title=Byrne for Alabama |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |author= |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date= |year= |month= |format= |work= |publisher= |pages= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref>  He was also a member of the [[Alabama State Senate]] from 2003 to 2007. He holds a degree from [[Duke University]], where he was a member of the [[Phi Delta Theta]] Fraternity, he also attended the [[University of Alabama]].<ref name=byrne1/> In December 2013, he won a special election to represent [[Alabama's 1st congressional district]] in the [[U.S. House of Representatives]].\n\n==Political background==\nByrne's first run for elective office was in 1994 was a success when he ran for the [[Alabama State Board of Education]] as a Democrat.<ref name=byrne1>{{cite news | first = | last = | authorlink = | author =Charles J. Dean | coauthors = | title =School Board Hopefuls Put Children First | url = | type =newspaper | work =Birmingham News | publisher =Birmingham News | location =Birmingham, Alabama | id = | pages = | page = | date =October 9, 1994 | accessdate =February 23, 2010 | quote = | archiveurl = | archivedate = }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news |author=Charles J. Dean |work=Birmingham News |publisher=Birmingham News| location=Birmingham, Alabama| accessdate=February 23, 2010 |title=Time of Change at State School Board Big Decisions Await Panel's Fresh Faces |page=101 |date=January 15, 1995}}</ref> During his term on the State Board of Education, Byrne supported a science curriculum that was opposed by many religious leaders in Alabama. He later voted with the Board to support a compromise that said, \"Explanations of the origin of life and major groups of plants and animals, including humans, shall be treated as theory and not as fact. When attempting to apply scientific knowledge to world problems, no social agenda shall be promoted.\" <ref name=\"Charles J. Dean 1A\">{{cite news |author=Charles J. Dean|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=Science Curriculum Gets Board Approval |page=1A |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |date =March 10, 1995}}</ref> In 1996 Byrne voted with the majority of Board members to reject $18 million in federal education funds because it was feared the money would allow greater federal control of schools. The vote was seen as a nod to the growing conservative influence in his south Alabama district.<ref name=\"Charles J. Dean 1A\"/> However Byrne later changed his mind and convinced the Board to allow the money <ref>{{cite news |author=Tom Gordon|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=Education Board's Byrne Will Join GOP Today |page=1B |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |date =January 9, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997 Byrne left the  [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] party and became a Republican.<ref>{{cite news |author=Tom Gordon|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=Win Every Office in State Party Chairman Tells GOP |page=22A |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |date =January 12, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 Byrne ran for an Alabama State Senate seat.<ref>{{cite news |author=Gary Mitchell|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=SBOE's Byrne enters GOP Race for Lipscomb's Seat |page=State and Regional |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |date =January 16, 2002}}</ref> He won with 91% of the vote over his Democratic challenger.<ref>{{cite news |author=|work=Birmingham News| publisher=Birmingham News| title=Alabama Senate Results |page=News |accessdate=February 23, 2010 |date =November 7, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Byrne sought and gained the Republican nomination for the United States House of Representatives, Alabama, District 1.<ref name=sawyer2013>{{cite news | first = | last = | authorlink = | author =Jessica Sawyer | coauthors = | title =Byrne wins, Young concedes in Alabama-01 Republican runoff | url =http://blog.al.com/live/2013/11/polls_close_at_7_pm_for_al-01.html | format =Digital | work =AL.com | publisher =Alabama Media Group, LLC | location = | id = | pages = | page = | date =November 5, 2013 | accessdate =November 6, 2013 | quote = | archiveurl = | archivedate = }}</ref>\n\n==Efforts against corruption==\nIn May 2007, Byrne took the position of community college chancellor <ref name=chanc>{{cite news |title=Byrne takes over |work=Mobile Register|location=Mobile, Alabama |page=B1 |author=George Altman|date=May 25, 2007|accessdate=February 24, 2010|type=newspaper}}</ref> and oversaw a controversial reordering of much of the system. [[Bishop State Community College]] in Mobile was the target of investigators who found both financial and academic issues at the school in 2006 and 2007. Byrne ordered an audit of the school which demonstrated many deficiencies. At the time, about 2 dozen people were charged with criminal fraud and theft charges. A total of 27 would be charged before the probe ended in May 2007 <ref name=chanc/><ref>{{cite news | first = | last = | authorlink = | author =George R. Altman | coauthors = | title =Auditors: Bishop showing progress | url = | type =newspaper | work =Mobile register | publisher =the Mobile Press register | location =Mobile, AL  | id = | pages = | page =B1 | date =September 12, 2008 | accessdate =February 23, 2010 | quote = | archiveurl = | archivedate = }}</ref>\n\nByrne also worked with Alabama Attorney General [[Troy King]] to recover monies stolen from the community college system.<ref>{{cite news | first = | last = | authorlink = | author = | coauthors = | title =Attorney general King announces lawsuit to recover funds stolen by defendants in postsecondary corruption cases | url = | type =newspaper | work =US States News | publisher = | location = | id = | pages = | page = | date = | accessdate = | quote = | archiveurl = | archivedate = }}</ref>\n\n==2010 gubernatorial campaign==\n{{main|Alabama gubernatorial election, 2010}}\n\nDuring the campaign, he was accused by his opponents in the Republican primary of supporting [[evolution]], to which he replied, \"As a Christian and as a public servant, I have never wavered in my belief that this world and everything in it is a masterpiece created by the hands of God ... As a member of the Alabama Board of Education, the record clearly shows that I fought to ensure the teaching of [[creationism]] in our school text books. Those who attack me have distorted, twisted and misrepresented my comments and are spewing utter lies to the people of this state.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20004740-503544.html?tag=contentMain;contentBody | work=CBS News | title=Alabama Gov. Candidate Attacked for Belief in Evolution}}</ref>\n\n;Endorsements\n{{div col|3}}\n*'''Individuals'''\n**[[Jeb Bush]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Bush Backs Byrne in Alabama|publisher=Politico.com|date=2010-03-05|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0310/34139.html}}</ref>\n**[[Jack Edwards (Alabama)|Jack Edwards]] (U.S. Rep. AL-1)<ref>{{cite video|title=Jack Edwards' Endorsement of Bradley Byrne|url=http://www.youtube.com/user/BradleyByrne#p/u/13/1o-mHSyZb_I}}</ref>\n**[[Jimmy Rane]] (President of [[Great Southern Wood]])<ref>{{cite video|title=Jimmy Rane's Endorsement of Bradley Byrne|url=http://www.youtube.com/user/BradleyByrne#p/u/10/_nPq-DzYCLo}}</ref>\n**Conservative Blogger Brian LeCompte; State Senator Ben Brooks; State Representatives Mike Ball, Phil Williams, Jamie Ison, Chad Fincher, Victor Gaston, and Jim Barton; Mobile City Council members John Williams, and Connie Hudson<ref>{{cite news|title=Various Individual Endorsements of Bradley Byrne|url=http://byrneforalabama.com/news/south_alabama_elected_officials_endorse_byrne/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title = Various Individual Endorsements of Bradley Byrne|url=http://byrneforalabama.com/news/byrne_endorsed_by_conservative_leaders_at_huntsville_campaign_fish_fry/}}</ref>\n*'''Associations'''\n**[[Alabama Retail Association]]<ref>{{cite news|title=RetailPAC Endorses Byrne for Governor|url=http://www.alabamaretail.org/news.aspx?id=26486}}</ref>\n**[[Alabama Home Builders Association]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Alabama Home Builders Association Endorses Bradley Byrne|url=http://byrneforalabama.com/news/home_builders_association_of_alabama_endorses_byrne_for_governor/}}</ref>\n**[[Alabama Association of Realtors]]<ref>{{cite video|title=REALTOR's Endorsment of Bradley Byrne|url=http://www.youtube.com/user/BradleyByrne#p/u/32/6leLO89T56A}}</ref>\n**[[Associated Builders and Contractors of Alabama]]<ref>{{cite video|title=ABC's Endoresment of Bradley Byrne|url=http://www.youtube.com/user/BradleyByrne#p/u/22/FLFgmKTV3lA}}</ref>\n**[[Right on Huntsville]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Right on Hunstville Endorses Bradley Byrne|url=http://byrneforalabama.com/news/byrne_endorsed_by_right_on_huntsville/}}</ref>\n*'''Newspapers'''\n**''[[The Birmingham News]]''<ref name=\"blog.al.com6\">{{cite news |url=http://blog.al.com/birmingham-news-commentary/2010/05/our_view_us_rep_artur_davis_an.html |title=OUR VIEW: U.S. Rep. Artur Davis and former two-year chancellor Bradley Byrne are their parties' best candidates |date=May 23, 2010}}</ref>\n**''[[The Mobile Press Register]]''<ref name=\"blog.al.com6\"/>\n**''[[The Huntsville Times]]''<ref name=\"blog.al.com6\"/>\n**''[[Opelika-Auburn News]]''<ref>{{cite news |title=Opelika-Auburn News Backs Byrne |url=http://www2.oanow.com/oan/OAN_Political_Blog/comments/oa_news_backs_byrne_davis/156456/}} {{dead link|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n**''[[Scottsboro Daily Sentinel]]''<ref>{{cite news |title=Digest of Byrne Endorsements |url=http://byrneforalabama.com/images/buttons/Bradley_Byrne_Newspaper_Endorsements.pdf}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Post-election activity==\nFollowing the run-off, Byrne went back to practicing business law, joining the Jones Walker law firm on August 16, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Bradley Byrne joins Jones Walker law firm |url=http://blog.al.com/businessnews/2010/08/bradley_byrne_joins_jones_walk.html |type=newspaper |publisher=[[AL.com]] |location = |date=August 16, 2010 |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n===Reform Alabama===\nOn February 23, 2011, Byrne announced he was partnering with other prominent Alabamians to create a [[nonprofit organization]] that would push for reforms in state government.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Despite losing GOP nomination for governor, Bradley Byrne still pressing for reforms |url=http://blog.al.com/breaking/2011/02/despite_losing_gop_nomination.html |newspaper=[[The Huntsville Times]] |location =[[Huntsville, AL]] |date=February 24, 2011 |accessdate= }}</ref> Named \"Reform Alabama\", the organization actively supported legislation in the 2011 Alabama Regular Legislative Session.<ref>{{cite web |first= |last= |work= |publisher= |title=Reform Alabama Legislation |url=http://reformalabama.org/legislation |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n===Possible Supreme Court run===\nA May 25, 2011 ''Mobile Press-Register'' article reported that Byrne was considering the possibility of running for [[chief justice]] of the [[Alabama Supreme Court]] in the upcoming 2012 election. \"I\u2019ve been encouraged to look at it, and I\u2019m doing that. But I\u2019ve made no decision, and frankly I\u2019m no where near a decision at this point,\" Byrne said.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Alabama Supreme Court race has lawyers buzzing |url=http://blog.al.com/live/2011/05/alabama_supreme_court_race_has.html |newspaper=[[Mobile Press-Register]] |location=[[Mobile, AL]] |date=May 25, 2011 |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n==2013 congressional campaign==\n{{See also|Alabama's 1st congressional district special election, 2013}}\nOn May 23, 2013, [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Jo Bonner]] announced that he would resign, effective on August 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite news |first=George |last=Talbot |title=Rep. Jo Bonner resignation stuns constituents, sparks candidates |url=http://blog.al.com/wire/2013/05/rep_jo_bonner_resignation_stun.html |publisher=[[AL.com]] |date=May 23, 2013 |accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref>  Byrne won the Republican primary and the November 5 runoff to become the nominee for the general election in December.\n\nByrne faced Dean Young in the runoff election who received the support of Tea Party voters. After the runoff, Young refused to endorse Byrne which led to rumors of a rift within the Republican Party. But Byrne subsequently gained the endorsement of Alabama Patriots, a Tea Party affiliated organization.<ref>{{cite news |first=Brendan |last=Kirby |title=Tea party group backs Byrne for Congress, disputes notion of rift in GOP |url=http://blog.al.com/live/2013/11/tea_party_group_back_byrne_for.html |newspaper=[[Mobile Press-Register]] |publisher=Alabama Media Group |date=November 12, 2013 |accessdate=November 12, 2013 }}</ref> Byrne won the Republican nomination for the congressional seat and faced Democratic Party nominee Burton LeFlore on December 17, 2013.<ref name=sawyer2013/><ref name=\"wapo131217\">{{cite news |first=Sean |last=Sullivan |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |location=[[Washington, DC]] |title=Republican Bradley Byrne wins Alabama special election |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/12/17/republican-bradley-byrne-wins-alabama-special-election/ |date=December 17, 2013 |accessdate=December 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==United States House of Representatives==\n===Tenure===\nByrne supported the [[Faithful Execution of the Law Act of 2014 (H.R. 3973; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of Justice]] to report to the [[United States Congress]] whenever any [[List of United States federal agencies|federal agency]] refrains from enforcing laws or regulations for any reason.<ref name=3973cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3973 - CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45177|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> In the report, the government would have to explain why it had decided not to enforce that law.<ref name=HtargetsObamalawEnf>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House targets Obama's law enforcement|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/government-oversight/200167-house-to-attack-obamas-non-enforcement-next-week|accessdate=12 March 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=7 March 2014}}</ref> Byrne spoke out in favor of the bill saying, \"the Obama Administration has been open and honest about one thing in particular: they have no problem making an end-run around Congress to achieve through administrative means what they cannot legislatively. Placing political convenience above the United States Constitution goes against everything the Founding Fathers intended, and it's time we put a stop to this practice.\"<ref name=ALpolRep>{{cite news|last=Moseley|first=Brandon|title=Byrne Co-Sponsors Act to Stop Selective Enforcement of the Law By Obama|url=http://alreporter.com/in-case-you-missed-it-2/5814-byrne-co-sponsors-act-to-stop-selective-enforcement-of-the-law-by-obama.html|accessdate=12 March 2014|newspaper=Alabama Political Reporter|date=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nByrne has sponsored two bills of his own:<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Byrne's Legislation|url=http://www.congress.gov/member/bradley-byrne/2197?q=%7B%22sponsorship%22%3A%22sponsored%22%2C%22type%22%3A%22bills%22%7D|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n* H.R. 4465, a bill to set catch limits for the Gulf of Mexico [[Northern red snapper|red snapper]] fishery, introduced April 10, 2014\n* H.R. 5510, a bill to require recognized accrediting agencies or associations that evaluate the quality of distance or correspondence education programs to require those programs to have a secure login and passcode for Internet coursework, introduced September 17, 2014\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Armed Services Committee]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower & Projection Forces]]\n*'''[[Natural Resources Committee]]'''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://byrne.house.gov/ Congressman Bradley Byrne] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.byrneforcongress.com/ Bradley Byrne for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Alabama/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Bradley_Byrne_%5BR-1%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = B001289 | nga = | nndb = | ballot = Bradley_Byrne | govtrack = 412601 | opencong = 412601 | our = 6738 | votesmart = 27584 | rollcall = 31423 | factcheck = | politifact = | fec = H4AL01123 | legistorm = | opensecrets = N00035380 | assets = | followthemoney = 4193 | ontheissues = House/Bradley_Byrne.htm | congress = bradley-byrne/2197 | worldcat = | c-span = bradleybyrne | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jo Bonner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Alabama|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Alabama's 1st congressional district]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Katherine Clark]]<br><small>D-[[Massachusetts]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=431st}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Jolly]]<br><small>R-[[Florida]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{AL-FedRep|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Personda